IU-SmartCert
A system for managing, distributing, using, revoking public keys, and issuing Ethereum-backed credentials. Requires issuers to endorse Ethereum accounts with an X.509 certificate signature.<SEP>IU-SmartCert is a blockchain-based educational credential management system with features for selective disclosure, defined by main user groups like issuers, learners, and relying parties.<SEP>IU-SmartCert is a system designed for managing digital credentials, involving schema definition and publishing data on the Ethereum blockchain.<SEP>IU-SmartCert is an organization that issues credentials verifiable through files, receipts, and the Ethereum network without contacting the issuing institution.

Blockchain
Blockchain serves as the foundational technology for IU-SmartCert, enabling secure, decentralized storage and verification of credentials via the Ethereum public blockchain.

Issuer
An issuer in IU-SmartCert context is any qualified individual or organization that issues educational credentials; they organize credentials into a format with mandatory and optional components and publish credential data to the blockchain.<SEP>An issuer in IU-SmartCert is responsible for defining schemas, providing credential components, and managing revocations.<SEP>The issuer is responsible for providing X.509 certificates and signing credentials via an Ethereum account.

Learner
A learner is an individual who receives credentials issued by an issuer, capable of selectively disclosing parts of their credentials as needed to relying parties.<SEP>A learner is an individual who receives digital credentials upon completing a program via the IU-SmartCert system.

Relying Party
A relying party refers to a person or company that uses and wants to verify the validity of a credential presented by learners.

Ethereum
Ethereum is a decentralized public blockchain platform used by IU-SmartCert for smart contract deployment, ensuring transparent and secure verification processes.

Credential Schema
A credential schema in IU-SmartCert is defined by issuers like universities to structure credentials into mandatory and optional components for flexibility in disclosure.

Mandatory Component
The mandatory component of a credential contains essential information needed for validation and evaluation, such as the diploma details of an undergraduate student.

Optional Components
Optional components allow issuers to create flexible credential data models, enabling learners to selectively disclose parts of their credentials.

Ethereum Blockchain
The Ethereum blockchain is used by IU-SmartCert to publish smart contracts, ensuring independent validation of digital credentials without contacting the issuer.

Merkle Tree
A Merkle tree is a data structure used in IU-SmartCert for constructing and validating digital credentials through cryptographic hashing.<SEP>A Merkle tree is a data structure used in blockchain technology to ensure the integrity of transaction records; it helps verify if a credential belongs to the correct set published on Ethereum.

Smart Contract
In IU-SmartCert, smart contracts on the Ethereum blockchain are utilized to store hashes of credentials' root nodes and manage revocations.

Digital Credentials
Digital credentials in IU-SmartCert are issued by educational institutions upon program completion, validated through a Merkle tree structure and published as smart contracts on the Ethereum blockchain.

Certificate Authority (CA)
A trusted Certificate Authority issues X.509 certificates to verify the identity of issuers in the IU-SmartCert system.

X.509 Certificate
An X.509 certificate is a digital certificate standard providing authentication for entities within the credential verification process, including issuer identification and signature validation.<SEP>An X.509 certificate is used by the issuer for establishing trust and verifying their identity through digital signatures.

CA (Certification Authority)
A Certification Authority that verifies issuer identity and digitally signs X.509 certificates to guarantee digital credentials' originality.

Ethereum account
A digital wallet used by issuers within the IU-SmartCert system to publish credentials, requiring endorsement with an X.509 certificate signature for credibility.

X.509 certificate
A standard for a public key infrastructure (PKI) that is endorsed by Ethereum accounts in the IU-SmartCert system and used to sign digital credentials.

Merkle tree
A data structure used within receipts to provide proofs of existence for credential components, enabling verification without revealing all data.

Smart contract
Contracts deployed on the Ethereum blockchain that manage credentials by storing information like transaction hashes and revocation lists.

Ethereum Network
The Ethereum network is a decentralized platform used to verify credentials by checking smart contract validity, signatures, and revocations as part of IU-SmartCert's verification process.
